content.description:
This is a great route except for it's only a couple of moves.  Move up the finger crack on the arete also using the small ledges on the faces.  Balance and high stepping skilz are a must. 

  I have not found this route in any guide books but I'm sure someone has climbed it before.  Let me know if there is a name for this route.
content.location: This route is directly behind the pillar of double crack.

content.description: Up the corner to a void slab then traverse across it and up.
content.protection: Thin passive, or top rope anchor
content.location: Just right of a cedar tree 30' south of Double Cracks.

content.description:
If Cobra is too much for you, get Mongoosed. Shorter climbers may find this harder than 5.8. Start at the bottom of the gully between Cobra and the Double Cracks block (exactly where Julie is standing in the 2nd edition guidebook photo, p. 105). Climb up a bit, using some holds on the Cobra face. Traverse left and pull over the roof (crux), then proceed to the top of the inside corner. An easier version (awkward 5.6) goes directly up the corner from the block above the tree.  

  BTW the next corner up the gully is short and guarded by loose rock at the bottom.
content.protection: No fixed gear. Trees and gear for toprope anchor

content.description: Up the left side of the keyhole face staying to the left as you climb.
content.protection: Set your top-rope to the left of the small summit prow.

content.description:
A direct line of the keyhole route.  Instead of heading right into the pod continue strait up to the top on small holds.  A very fun route. 

 RCM&W #60, P.167.
content.protection: The pro dissapears after deviating from the standard route so I would not recommend leading, unless you can find something I didn't see.  Same top rope setup as keyhole.  Nuts, and webbing for the large boulders.
content.location: Immediately to the left of the standard keyhole route.

content.description:
Follow the thin crack, up to a large pod to the right.  Continue up and angle back toward the left. 

 RCM&W #59, p.167.
content.protection: Nuts and cams.  Mostly small stuff, nothing bigger than small hands is needed.  For the top rope setup, webbing for slinging boulders and a small nut placement is all I could come up with.
content.location: Keyhole is the main route in the area, the top is located slightly north of the overlook.  To reach the top walk around the overlook from the right and continue under the base of the overlook around some large boulders to a ledge.  The ledge is the top of the keyhole face.

content.description: Slabby, requires good footwork.  It does have a good variety of body movements.
content.protection: Solid top-rope set up, small to medium pro on lead
content.location: Up and right of the Keyhole, stay in the small seam

content.description:
Climb the somewhat slabby face to the top of the column.  This route wanders a bit between the left and right side of the face.  Not worth the trip on its own but enjoyable if you happen to be in the area. 

 RCM&W #63, p.167.
content.protection: Top rope from the top of the block.  Slings/webbing and carabiners are all that is needed.
content.location: A face climb around the corner left from Double Cracks.

content.description:
Scramble up next to the tree, left of Double Cracks and Hamburger Helper. Few fun moves through the short crack in the dihedral up top. 

  RCM&W #64 p.167
content.protection: Protects well, crack is wide up top. Std rack.
content.location:
Route is in the keyhole area. Starts at the base of Hamburger Helper and climbs up and slightly left.  

This route is a great way to rap down into the Keyhole Area, there's trees and decent pro up top for TR.

  From the top - at the end of the next overlook after the old parking lot follow the small trail once the stone wall ends. The top of the route is down and to the left.

content.description: Follow the double crack system to the top of the block, using a combination of face hold, hand jams, and finger jams. This is a fun route to put someone on who does not have a solid basis in crack technique. They tend to flail at the bottom. Using just the left crack earns you a 5.10 rating.
content.protection: Nuts, and cams, nothing bigger than thin hands is needed.  For the top rope setup slings or webbing and carabiners are all that is needed.
content.location: About 15 yards climber's left and downhill of the keyhole is a large freestanding block.  This route is found on the face facing the St. Croix River.  To reach the top to set up top rope, scramble up a gully to the left of the keyhole route and to the right of this formation.
